04571nam a22006135i 9780822388487DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223884877 a10.1515/97808223884872doi  a(DE-B1597)554078  a(OCoLC)1167514890  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM706b.P68 2006 7aPSY0160002bisacsh1 aPovinelli, Elizabeth A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Empire of Love :bToward a Theory of Intimacy, Genealogy, and Carnality /cElizabeth A. Povinelli; Dilip Parameshwar Gaonkar, Michael Warner, Benjamin Lee, Jane Kramer. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPublic planet books00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tEmpires of Love: An Introduction -- t1 Rotten Worlds -- t2 Spiritual Freedom, Cultural Copyright -- t3 The Intimate Event and Genealogical Society -- tNotes -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Empire of Love anthropologist Elizabeth A. Povinelli reflects on a set of ethical and normative claims about the governance of love, sociality, and the body that circulates in liberal settler colonies such as the United States and Australia. She boldly theorizes intimate relations as pivotal sites where liberal logics and aspirations absorbed through settler imperialism are manifest, where discourses of self-sovereignty, social constraint, and value converge.For more than twenty years, Povinelli has traveled to the social worlds of indigenous men and women living at Belyuen, a small community in the Northern Territory of Australia. More recently she has moved across communities of alternative progressive queer movements in the United States, particularly those who identify as radical faeries. In this book she traces how liberal binary concepts of individual freedom and social constraint influence understandings of intimacy in these two worlds. At the same time, she describes alternative models of social relations within each group in order to highlight modes of intimacy that transcend a reductive choice between freedom and constraint.Shifting focus away from identities toward the social matrices out of which identities and divisions emerge, Povinelli offers a framework for thinking through such issues as what counts as sexuality and which forms of intimate social relations result in the distribution of rights, recognition, and resources, and which do not. In The Empire of Love Povinelli calls for, and begins to formulate, a politics of "thick life," a way of representing social life nuanced enough to meet the density and variation of actual social worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIntimacy (Psychology). 0aLove. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aSocial structure. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality (see also SOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Sexuality).2bisacsh1 aGaonkar, Dilip Parameshwar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKramer, Jane, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWarner, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388487zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388487.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles